SwiftUI is not like Cocoa. It is not event-driven, and there is no communication from one interface object to another. There is only _data_. Data flows thru _state variables_. It flows _up_ by a state variable&#39;s _binding_ and _down_ by a state variable&#39;s _value_.

So you don&#39;t need an `onEditingChanged` event, or any other event. `$totalAmount` is a _binding_. It changes when the text field&#39;s text changes, _automatically_. 

Moreover, `totalAmount` is a _state variable._ If the Text uses this as its value, directly or indirectly, the text changes _automatically_ when `totalAmount` changes. 

So just use a calculated variable that depends on `totalAmount` and make that the value of the Text and you&#39;re done. 

Extremely basic example:

    struct ContentView : View {
        @State var totalAmount = &quot;&quot;
        let addAmount = 10.0 // or whatever
        var calc : Double { (Double(totalAmount) ?? 0.0) + addAmount } // or whatever
        var body: some View {
            HStack {
                TextField(&quot;Type a number&quot;, text: $totalAmount)
                    .textFieldStyle(RoundedBorderTextFieldStyle())
                    .frame(width:100)
                Text(String(self.calc))
            }
        }
    }

